IN THE 1940S PEOPLE OFTEN LIVED WHERE THEY WORKED.
RAYMOND IS TELLING HIS DAUGHTER ABOUT HOW HE GREW UP.
HE ORIGINALLY THOUGHT HE WAS RICH BUT HIS PARENTS TOLD HIM OTHERWISE.
HIS FATHER GOT A JOB AS A LIBRARY CUSTODIAN AND THEY MOVED INTO THE LIBRARY.
HE WAS ASHAMED OF IT AT FIRST AND DID NOT INVITE ANY OF HIS FRIENDS OVER TO HIS PLACE.
BUT EVENTUALLY HE SAW HOW FORTUNATE HE ACTUALLY WAS.
HE HAD TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAY BUT ONCE THE LIBRARY CLOSED, HE COULD DO WHATEVER HE WANTED AND READ AS MANY BOOKS AS HE WANTED.
HE OFTEN WOULD GET UP IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT AND READ JUST TO ANSWER QUESTIONS THAT HE HAD.
HE ENDED UP BEING THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL AND THEN GRADUATE COLLEGE.
HE TOOK A JOB TEACHING AT A COLLEGE AND TOOK HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM ONE DAY.
HIS FATHER DID NOT SAY MUCH BUT RAYMOND COULD TELL THAT HE WAS PROUD.
IN THE 1940S A LOT OF PEOPLE LIVED WHERE THEY WORKED.
RAYMOND WAS TELLING HIS DAUGHTER HOW HE THOUGHT HE WAS RICH AS A CHILD BUT WHEN SAYING SO TO HIS PARENTS, THEY CORRECTED HIM SAYING THAT THEY WERE IN FACT POOR.
NOT LONG AFTER THAT, RAYMOND'S FATHER TOOK A JOB AS A LIBRARY CUSTODIAN.
THEY THEN MOVED TO THE LIBRARY.
AT FIRST RAYMOND WAS ASHAMED OF THIS AND NEVER INVITED ANY OF HIS FRIENDS OVER TO VISIT.
BUT EVENTUALLY HE LEARNED THAT HE WAS VERY FORTUNATE.
HIS FATHER WAS ALSO THE BEST LIBRARY CUSTODIAN TOO.
HE NEVER ALLOWED TRASH TO BE ON THE GROUND AND EVEN WAXED THE TOP OF THE BOOKSHELVES.
RAYMOND HAD TO BE QUIET DURING THE DAY BUT ONCE THE LIBRARY WAS CLOSED HE COULD RUN AROUND AND DO ANYTHING IN IT.
HE COULD ALSO READ WHATEVER BOOK HE WANTED AND OFTEN STAYED UP UNTIL 3AM READING AND LOOKING UP ANSWERS TO QUESTIONS HE HAD.
HE WAS THE FIRST PERSON IN HIS FAMILY TO MAKE IT PAST HIGH SCHOOL AND GRADUATE FROM COLLEGE.
HE TOOK A JOB AS A PROFESSOR AND INVITED HIS FATHER TO SEE HIS CLASSROOM AND DOOR.
HE FATHER WAS VERY QUIET BUT RAYMOND COULD TELL THAT HE WAS PROUD OF HIM
